# TypeScript / React / Next.js Conventions

- Use strict TypeScript patterns and explicit boundaries for untrusted data.
- Exported functions should use explicit return types when practical.
- Prefer `interface` for public object contracts; use `type` for unions/aliases.
- Avoid enums; prefer `as const` objects/maps.
- Narrow types early and use exhaustive switches for unions.
- Default to React Server Components; keep client islands small.
- Minimize `useEffect` and unnecessary client state.
- Follow Next.js App Router patterns for routing, loading, and error states.
- Use semantic HTML by default.

# SOLID in TS/React Practice

- Model features as small, cohesive modules (SRP), not large utility buckets.
- Keep extension points explicit (OCP): strategy maps, handler registries, or focused adapters where variation is real.
- Ensure interchangeable implementations keep the same behavior contract (LSP), not just the same type signature.
- Split broad contracts into focused interfaces/function contracts (ISP) so consumers import only what they need.
- Keep app/business logic dependent on ports/contracts, with concrete clients in adapter modules (DIP).
- In React/Next, keep UI components thin and delegate policy/business decisions to domain/application modules.
